{
  "text": "One functional parameter that has been largely evaluated in malnutritional conditions is the thymic hormone production by TEC. It was initially found that that proteinmalnourished mice exhibited abnormally low levels of circulating thymulin [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and that such a decrease was also observed in protein-malnourished rats and human subjects [CITATION_3] . Interestingly, even in human subjects protein malnutrition secondary to anorexia nervosa, low thymulin serum levels were reported [CITATION_4] . Furthermore, decreased thymulin serum levels were reported in mice submitted to diets designed to trigger deficiency in Zn, Fe, or vitamins [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . At least regarding Zn deficiency, similar results were found in human subjects [CITATION_8] . It is noteworthy that the decrease in thymic hormone serum levels seen in malnutrition is not restricted to thymulin, since it was recently reported with regard to thymopoietin production [CITATION_9] . In this study, the authors further demonstrated that prenatal undernutrition was significantly associated with reduced thymopoietin production in interaction with the duration of exclusive breast-feeding. These findings provide support for the importance of fetal and early infant programming of thymic function, and longterm implications for the immune system, and consequently adult disease risk.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "30386469",
    "[CITATION_2]": "45831920",
